pullRequest.body:
Establishes locality properties of meromorphic functions in normal form, analogous to existing statements for analytic functions. Establishes that meromorphic functions have normal form outside of a codiscrete set. Describes the vanishing locus in terms of the order function. Establishes elementary criteria to guarantee normal form.

**Caveat Emptor!** This PR re-installs a theorem `AnalyticAt.eventuallyEq_nhdNE_iff_eventuallyEq_nhd` that was previously criticised by reviewers. It adds an analogous theorem `MeromorphicNFAt.eventuallyEq_nhdNE_iff_eventuallyEq_nhd` for meromorphic functions in normal form. The reason for bringing these theorems back is that they are used throughout [Project VD](https://github.com/kebekus/ProjectVD), which aims to formalize Value Distribution Theory for meromorphic functions on the complex plane. I will bring the issue up on [Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/API.20for.20continuous.20extension.20of.20meromorphic.20functions) and downgrade the PR to "draft" while the discussion is going.

Yes. No. Yes. I mean, yes … but …

Long story: the statement you write down is true, but for a misleading reason. If `X` is a topological space [or even a metric space] and `f`, `g` are functions on `X`, then the statement is wrong in general. The simplest counterexample is that where `z₀` is an isolated point. The reason that it will work here is that the topologies of nontrivially normed fields are special …

I tried to write down the proof of your statement, and it quickly became long, protracted and absolutely awful. That was the point where I gave up last time. IMHO, it would make sense to leave the current, simple & easy theorem untouched, and add the philosophical correct statement to the topology section. But even with that in place, the current proof of the current statement might be easier than a proof using the topological statement, which would require us to go into the "nontrivially normed" condition…

Does that make sense? Or am I on the wrong path?

Doesn't it work iff `z₀` isn't isolated? If so, you can state that `z₀` isn't an isolated point by doing `(𝓝[≠] z₀).NeBot`, or some similar filter statement (I think that's the correct one but I'm not super sharp at this filter stuff). Hopefully, the proof becomes easier too

* `ENat.map (Nat.cast : ℕ → α) n = 0 ↔ n = 0` if `[AddMonoidWithOne α] [PartialOrder α] [AddLeftMono α] [ZeroLEOneClass α] [CharZero α]`
